{"id": "12781", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12781", "title": "Magic Flute", "text": "Magic Flute is a &lt;a href=\"high-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;high-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; that creates a magic flute made of pure magical energy. When played, the flute can be used to cast the following spells:\nThe spell-like abilities on the Flute are used in the same way that a wand's powers are used. Unlike normal spellcasting, using the flute is not interrupted when taking damage. The Flute lasts for 1 day. This ability can only be selected by &lt;a href=\"bard\"&gt;bard&lt;/a&gt;s. It can only be taken once, meaning you only get to create one flute per rest."}
{"id": "27801", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27801", "title": "Magic Golem", "text": "The Magic Golem is a construct created by a &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt;. They are first encountered in \"\", or in if visiting Watcher's Keep before chapter 7.\nGameplay.\nThis golem is mostly immune to all magical effects, spells, magical weapons of any type, and elemental damage.\nSee the InfoBox summary of immunities and protections.\nThe creature has a unique attack with a ranged weapon that manifests as a +3 enchanted ranged attack (using the beholder blast projectile), which must roll to hit a target.\nIf the weapon scores a hit, it inflicts &lt;a href=\"Missile%20damage\"&gt;Missile damage&lt;/a&gt; that is augmented by the golem's strength bonus.\nThe special on-hit effect of the weapon is to drain item charges (including weapons) that are in the character's quick item slots or worn/equipped.\nAlso, if the target has memorized Wizard spells available, one spell (starting at the highest level) will be expended and not be available until resting occurs.\nThe creature is otherwise vulnerable to normal weapons and fists (monk class may have magical fists/kick, which won't strike the golem).\nNote that fist attacks won't actually slay the creature, as they deal stunning/non-lethal damage. Fist blows can make the creature fall down in a semi-unconscious state, at least for a period of time. Best to find a non-magical weapon or ammunition (any type will do) to finish it off.\nThe creature's battle action scripting attempts to keep a distance from attackers, staying out of melee range, so as to get better performance from its ranged attack. \nNote.\nThe golem's attack uses the same projectile as a &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;Beholder&lt;/a&gt; blast, and thus, the &lt;a href=\"Shield%20of%20Balduran\"&gt;Shield of Balduran&lt;/a&gt; can reflect it back (which won't be able to hit the golem, as it is a magical attack).\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes some revisions to this creature.\nThe golem is immune to the spells &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower Resistance&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Magic\"&gt;Pierce Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Shield\"&gt;Pierce Shield&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Plant%20Growth\"&gt;Plant Growth&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe status effects &lt;a href=\"Webbed\"&gt;Webbed&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Entangle\"&gt;Entangle&lt;/a&gt; is added to the list of immunities.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Construction%20for%20Spellcasters\"&gt;Golem Construction for Spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; mod revises Magic Golems and adds a special innate ability called \"Wild Magic Flare\" that is used at the outset of hostilities and directed at the first detected enemy - after a few rounds it can be used again.\nThe Flare can be blocked by Magic resistance, but there is no saving throw. The effects on the target are a varied collection of Wild magic possibilities rolled on a d100 percentile die."}
{"id": "33872", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=33872", "title": "Magic License in Athkatla", "text": "The Cowled Wizards are an organization that regulates and enforces magic laws within &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Cowled Wizards place strict laws forbidding casting unlicensed arcane spells in Athkatla. The casting of one will lead to the arrest of those involved. If they resist, they will be killed. After they are arrested, they go on trial in a building in the Athkatla Government, where the leader decides what punishment they receive. They can be executed, or they may be sent to Spellhold, an asylum for magical deviants.\nThe license to cast arcane spells can be purchased from &lt;a href=\"Corneil\"&gt;Corneil&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Council%20of%20Six%20Building\"&gt;Council of Six Building&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Government\"&gt;Athkatla Government&lt;/a&gt; district for 5,000 gold. If you purchase a license, no more enforcers will appear. Otherwise, the first time an arcane spell is cast, you will get a warning from a Cowled Wizard who teleports in. The next five times, he will summon three other enforcers and all of them will attack you. If you defeat them, you then have one hour in which you can cast arcane spells freely without anyone responding.\nOn the final time after the warning, the responding wizard will summon three much more powerful mages: a 16th-level Cowled Wizard worth 6,000 XP, an 18th-level Cowled Wizard worth 20,000 XP, and a 30th-level mage named &lt;a href=\"Zallanora\"&gt;Zallanora&lt;/a&gt; worth 6,000 XP. They are armed with high level spells like Time Stop, Power Word Kill, Abi-Dalzim's Horrid Wilting, Simulacrum (which can result in an extra wizard opposing you) and more... Once you succeed in killing them, there will be no further response to any arcane spellcasting in Athkatla: and, indeed, should you decide to go back and purchase a license after having proved your point in such a drastic manner, you will not have the option to do so, the game will treat you as if you already have one.\nNote: While a majority of players will buy the license to have freedom and no trouble in playing, many won't pay and will instead adjust to the gaming style of no arcane spellcasting inside the city. If desired, you can do so until the party is strong enough to actively lure in the enforcers for\u00a0their XP and loot.\nNote: On the matter of roleplay, The Cowled Wizards do not represent the lawful government. They set down the law and they go out to enforce it without the government's approval. &lt;a href=\"Chief%20Inspector%20Brega\"&gt;Chief Inspector Brega&lt;/a&gt; is quite eloquent about this. Thus, it's not against Lawful alignment to kill them. Even Keldorn doesn't twitch an eyebrow.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod has two optional components that can be installed regarding the Cowled Wizards:\nAllow the Cowled Wizards to detect spellcasting in most indoor, above-ground areas in Athkatla (BG2,BG2EE,BGT)\nThe Cowled Wizards claim to ban magic everywhere in Athkatla; in practice, though, they only complain if you cast spells out of doors. This component extends their watch to most indoor, above-ground areas in Athkatla (there are a few exceptions, mostly places where wizards live (e.g. Prebek's tower) or where it's likely that the owners have made arrangements with the Cowled Wizards (e.g. the Copper Coronet).\nIncrease the price of a license to practice magic in Athkatla (BG2, BG2EE, BGT)\nThe default price for a magic license from the Cowled Wizards is 5,000gp. This component allows you to increase it to an amount between 10,000gp and 50,000gp, depending on which option you choose during installation. These options are useful to realistically manage the abundant gold that accumulates, well beyond the player's needs, to make the party's purse feel more realistic and balanced. Otherwise, money is never an issue in the game - and it probably should be a factor that needs to be considered, and a resource with implications."}
{"id": "3425", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3425", "title": "Magic Missile", "text": "When Magic Missile is cast, a scintillating missile of magical energy is directed forth from the wizard's fingertip towards a targeted creature.\nGameplay.\nThe caster selects a single creature to target the magic missile to, using the targeting cursor.\nWhen the spell casting is finished one or more projectiles dart forth and fly unerringly to the target.\nThe victim is struck by 1 to 5 missiles, as determined by the caster's mage level, and each missile inflicts 1d4+1 &lt;a href=\"Magical%20damage\"&gt;Magical damage&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis spell can be blocked by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;, any &lt;a href=\"Spell%20protections%20type\"&gt;Spell protections type&lt;/a&gt; such as &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;.\nA &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Minor Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt; will bounce the missiles back to the caster.\nA creature protected with a &lt;a href=\"Shield%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Shield (spell)&lt;/a&gt; will be immune.\nAdditionally, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Evocation&lt;/a&gt; will negate the spell, as will the &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Mirroring\"&gt;Cloak of Mirroring&lt;/a&gt;.\nA creature protected by &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; will potentially fool the missiles, and one good use of the spell is to rapidly destroy a number of images using this spell, especially when cast at the 9th level.\nAs the spell is quickly cast, this spell remains useful throughout the saga for its ability to disrupt targets in the midst of spell casting or apply damage rapidly.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition Wizard spell \"Magic Missile\" can target more than one creature when the wizard has multiple missiles. The Wizard's Compendium alternative rules allow up to nine magic missiles for a 17th level Wizard."}
{"id": "4042", "revid": "4517063", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4042", "title": "Magic Missiles", "text": ""}
{"id": "30653", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30653", "title": "Magic Resistance", "text": ""}
{"id": "5466", "revid": "269009", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5466", "title": "Magic Resistance (spell)", "text": "Magic Resistance sets the target creature's &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; to 2% per caster level up to 40% at 20th level.\nGameplay.\nThe first experience level that a cleric can use this spell is level 9. Using this as an example, when cast by the level 9 cleric, the spell will set the target's &lt;a href=\"magic%20resistance\"&gt;magic resistance&lt;/a&gt; to 18% (9 x 2%), making it an excellent \"debuff\" when encountering powerful, magic resistant creatures such as dragons. The spell basically overwrites the creature's innate MR rating and gets reset (temporarily) with the new value. This works in favor of the attacker.\nThis spell pierces through pre-existing &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;. It can be used on opponents instead of &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower Resistance&lt;/a&gt; in order to scale down their natural MR and memorize less &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Magic\"&gt;Pierce Magic&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Shield\"&gt;Pierce Shield&lt;/a&gt; on mages. Keep in mind however, that Magic Resistance is a touch spell with the highest possible casting time (9), which makes it difficult to apply it on enemies, whereas all the wizard spells to lower resistance have maximum range and shorter casting time.\nWhen cast on a party member it will completely override any magical resistance from items or abilities. Additional castings are not cumulative.\nThis spell can be removed with spell protection removers such as &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Thrust\"&gt;Spell Thrust&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Secret%20Word\"&gt;Secret Word&lt;/a&gt;. The spell can also be dispelled via &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt;.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this divine spell, revising its casting time, duration and description. See below:\nMagic Resistance\nLevel: 5\nSchool: Alteration\nSphere: Protection\nRange: Touch\nDuration: 2 rounds/level\nCasting Time: 5\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: None\nUpon the casting of this spell, the recipient\u2019s resistance to all forms of magic is increased by 2% per level of the priest, up to a maximum bonus of 40% at 20th level. This effect will last for the duration of the spell or until dispelled. Multiple castings of this spell are not cumulative."}
{"id": "20826", "revid": "978785", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20826", "title": "Magic Stone", "text": ""}
{"id": "51558", "revid": "50936485", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51558", "title": "Magic attack type", "text": "Magic attack is a secondary spell type (the primary type being the school of magic). The phrase \"magic attack\" should be thought of as \"an attack against magic\" rather than \"an attack that is magical\": spells of this type usually destroy &lt;a href=\"Spell%20protections%20type\"&gt;Spell protections&lt;/a&gt; and other buffs, though many types of dragon breaths are also classified as magic attacks. Examples of Magic attacks include &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt;, like &lt;a href=\"Spellstrike\"&gt;Spellstrike&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Black%20Dragon%20Breath\"&gt;Black Dragon Breath&lt;/a&gt;.\nMechanics.\nThe Magic attack spell type explicitly bypasses &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity&lt;/a&gt;, (&lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor&lt;/a&gt;) &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;, (&lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Minor&lt;/a&gt;) &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Trap\"&gt;Spell Trap&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Shield%20of%20the%20Archons\"&gt;Shield of the Archons&lt;/a&gt;, because the defense they provide relies on effects that purposefully let Magic attacks through.\n(&lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor&lt;/a&gt;) &lt;a href=\"Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magic\"&gt;Protection From Magic&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Magic%20Blocking\"&gt;Potion of Magic Blocking&lt;/a&gt;, on the other hand, are able to block Magic attacks when they carry effects of the right &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;level&lt;/a&gt;. Most Magic attacks cast against player characters, however, carry &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;level 0&lt;/a&gt; effects, which none of these level-based protections can handle. Against these attacks, the best and often only defense is &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Shield\"&gt;Spell Shield&lt;/a&gt;. It grants one level worth of immunity to all Magic attacks, without exception, but exhausts itself by the level of the thwarted attack. Level 0 attacks are not only blocked, but cannot exhaust the shield, making it most useful against them. The full list of non-zero Magic attacks can be found in Spell Shield's wiki article.\nList of magic attacks.\nIn and the original edition of , the &lt;a href=\"Wing%20Buffet\"&gt;Wing Buffet&lt;/a&gt; of all dragons is of the Magic attack type. Wilful transformation into the Slayer also belongs to this type in the original BGII.\nMod gallery.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod implements changes to Dragon Breath weapons - which should not be blocked by Spell Immunity or be classified as Magic attack type effects.\nBreath weapon attacks are revised and not assigned to spell schools and are no longer Magic attack type either. For example, the Shadow Dragon &lt;a href=\"Thaxll%27ssillyia\"&gt;Thaxll'ssillyia&lt;/a&gt; breath attack is no longer of the magic attack type."}
{"id": "32662", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32662", "title": "Magic damage", "text": ""}
{"id": "32664", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32664", "title": "Magic damage resistance", "text": ""}
{"id": "27797", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27797", "title": "Magic missile", "text": ""}
{"id": "30654", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30654", "title": "Magic resistance", "text": "Magic resistance (MR) is a \u2013 sometimes natural \u2013 &lt;a href=\"status%20effect\"&gt;status effect&lt;/a&gt; applied to a &lt;a href=\"creature\"&gt;creature&lt;/a&gt; which determines the chance that a hostile &lt;a href=\"spell\"&gt;spell&lt;/a&gt; cast on the creature will outright fail and spell effects not be applied. Friendly spells and potions are not affected by MR.\nEven if the MR check fails, a saving throw may still prevent the spell. For example, a hostile wizard casts &lt;a href=\"Charm%20Person\"&gt;Charm Person&lt;/a&gt; on &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and she fails the Magic Resistance check. A &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;save vs. spell&lt;/a&gt; check is now rolled and if she succeeds, she will not be charmed.\nAgainst spells which create multiple projectiles (like &lt;a href=\"Magic%20Missile\"&gt;Magic Missile&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Flame%20Arrow\"&gt;Flame Arrow&lt;/a&gt;), MR is checked individually for each projectile.\nSome &lt;a href=\"race\"&gt;race&lt;/a&gt;s, such as the &lt;a href=\"drow\"&gt;drow&lt;/a&gt;, have inherent magic resistance. Many &lt;a href=\"item\"&gt;item&lt;/a&gt;s grant a certain, often accumulative magic resistance to their wearer or consumer.\nEnemy magic resistance can be lowered with the following spells: &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower Resistance&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Magic\"&gt;Pierce Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Shield\"&gt;Pierce Shield&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Magic%20Resistance%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Magic Resistance&lt;/a&gt; (if spell output determined by formula [caster level]*2% is lower than creature's natural magic resistance). Those themselves cannot be stopped by MR.\nSome spells bypass magic resistance. These include &lt;a href=\"Bolt%20of%20Glory\"&gt;Bolt of Glory&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dragon%27s%20Breath\"&gt;Dragon's Breath&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Fire%20Storm\"&gt;Fire Storm&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Implosion\"&gt;Implosion&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shocking%20Grasp\"&gt;Shocking Grasp&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Imprisonment\"&gt;Imprisonment&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Energy%20Drain\"&gt;Energy Drain&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Contagion\"&gt;Contagion&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Deafness\"&gt;Deafness&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Teleport%20Field\"&gt;Teleport Field&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"False%20Dawn\"&gt;False Dawn&lt;/a&gt; (on undead), &lt;a href=\"Blade%20Barrier\"&gt;Blade Barrier&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Globe%20of%20Blades\"&gt;Globe of Blades&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Fireshield\"&gt;Fireshield&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Aura%20of%20Flaming%20Death\"&gt;Aura of Flaming Death&lt;/a&gt;, the damage of &lt;a href=\"Earthquake\"&gt;Earthquake&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Chain%20Lightning\"&gt;Chain Lightning&lt;/a&gt; when cast by an &lt;a href=\"Avenger\"&gt;Avenger&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower Resistance&lt;/a&gt; and other spells that target MR, &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt;, spells that attack/strip magical defenses, spells like &lt;a href=\"True%20Sight\"&gt;True Sight&lt;/a&gt; that dispel invisibility / illusions, spells that summon weapons or throwable projectiles like &lt;a href=\"Melf%27s%20Minute%20Meteors\"&gt;Melf's Minute Meteors&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Sol%27s%20Searing%20Orb\"&gt;Sol's Searing Orb&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Shillelagh\"&gt;Shillelagh&lt;/a&gt;, the unconsciousness effect of &lt;a href=\"Comet\"&gt;Comet&lt;/a&gt;, the death effect of &lt;a href=\"Slay%20Living\"&gt;Slay Living&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Time%20Stop\"&gt;Time Stop&lt;/a&gt;. In the non EE games, &lt;a href=\"Sunfire\"&gt;Sunfire&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Glitterdust\"&gt;Glitterdust&lt;/a&gt; also bypass MR. See also . It is still possible to become immune to some of these spells, either by using an appropriate &lt;a href=\"Spell%20protections%20type\"&gt;spell protection spell&lt;/a&gt; or by using the rare &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magic\"&gt;Protection From Magic&lt;/a&gt; scrolls. Immunities to certain spell levels (&lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Magic%20Blocking\"&gt;Potion of Magic Blocking&lt;/a&gt;, innate immunities of &lt;a href=\"Lich\"&gt;Lich&lt;/a&gt;es and &lt;a href=\"Rakshasa\"&gt;Rakshasa&lt;/a&gt;s) also completely block spells, even those that bypass MR.\nMagic resistance also applies to some effects tied to or items, but not to others; this differs from case to case. For example, &lt;a href=\"Jester%20Song\"&gt;Jester Song&lt;/a&gt; ignores MR, but a Blackguard's &lt;a href=\"Aura%20of%20Despair\"&gt;Aura of Despair&lt;/a&gt; is blocked by MR. An item can also have different applications for multiple effects, e.g. &lt;a href=\"Celestial%20Fury\"&gt;Celestial Fury&lt;/a&gt; blindness bypasses MR, but its lightning strike does not.\nMagic resistance can be above 100%, up to 127%. Resistance over 100% provides no direct benefits, but is an additional layer of protection against &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower Resistance&lt;/a&gt;.\nImproving magic resistance.\nTemporary bonuses.\nAbilities.\nShapeshift\nMagic Damage Resistance (MDR).\nMagic resistance is different from to &lt;a href=\"magical%20damage\"&gt;magical damage&lt;/a&gt;: magic(al) damage resistance reduces (positive) or amplifies (negative) the &lt;a href=\"damage\"&gt;damage&lt;/a&gt; a creature would take if a spell dealing magical damage gets through the former and is applied after any reduction from a saving throw (if one applies). \nFor example, let's say a character with 50% magic resistance is hit by a &lt;a href=\"Skull%20Trap\"&gt;Skull Trap&lt;/a&gt;. If the MR check succeeds, no damage will be taken. If the MR check fails, a saving throw is performed to determine whether full or half damage is to be applied, and finally is applied. If MDR is negative more damage is applied than what's left after the saving throw.\nMagic Damage Resistance has a hard cap of 127 in either direction. A Magic Damage Resistance over 100% means the character is healed when taking magical damage."}
{"id": "30431", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30431", "title": "Magical Entrapments", "text": ""}
{"id": "50605", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50605", "title": "Magical Item Merchant", "text": "The Magical Item Merchant is a rather silent &lt;a href=\"Illithid\"&gt;Illithid&lt;/a&gt; merchant serving in the Black Pits arena of &lt;a href=\"Thay\"&gt;Thay&lt;/a&gt;. This is new content created by &lt;a href=\"Beamdog\"&gt;Beamdog&lt;/a&gt;.\nStore in The Black Pits II.\nTier 2 additions.\nThe game tries to add a &lt;a href=\"Rod%20of%20Resurrection\"&gt;Rod of Resurrection&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Rod%20of%20Reversal\"&gt;Rod of Reversal&lt;/a&gt; both with 5 charges, but fails.\nA second Ring of Regeneration will also be added, but only if there isn't any in the shop when reaching tier 2.\nTier 3 additions.\nA second pair of Paws of the Cheetah will be added, but only if there isn't any in the shop when reaching tier 3.\nTier 4 additions.\nThe game tries to add a &lt;a href=\"Greenstone%20Amulet\"&gt;Greenstone Amulet&lt;/a&gt; with 10 charges, but fails.\nYet another pair of Paws of the Cheetah will be added, but only if there isn't any in the shop when reaching tier 4.\nTier 5 additions.\nThe game tries to add &lt;a href=\"Gargoyle%20Boots\"&gt;Gargoyle Boots&lt;/a&gt;, but fails.\nA final pair of Paws of the Cheetah will be added, but only if there isn't any in the shop when reaching tier 5."}
{"id": "30801", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30801", "title": "Slow Poison", "text": "Slow Poison may refer to:"}
{"id": "30782", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30782", "title": "Slow Poison (ability)", "text": "Slow Poison is an &lt;a href=\"innate%20ability\"&gt;innate ability&lt;/a&gt; that the &lt;a href=\"companion\"&gt;companion&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Dynaheir\"&gt;Dynaheir&lt;/a&gt; may use once per day.\nAdditionally, &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; may gain uses during the \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\" campaign. It is identical to the 2nd level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt; of the &lt;a href=\"Slow%20Poison%20%28spell%29\"&gt;same name&lt;/a&gt;, except that it is not subject to silence (as it is not a spell).\nIt can be gained during &lt;a href=\"Dreams%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%29\"&gt;dream sequence 3 and 4&lt;/a&gt; if the party's &lt;a href=\"reputation\"&gt;reputation&lt;/a&gt; is 10 or greater; if it is less, then the protagonist will gain &lt;a href=\"Ghoul%20Touch%20%28ability%29\"&gt;Ghoul Touch&lt;/a&gt; / &lt;a href=\"Horror%20%28ability%29\"&gt;Horror&lt;/a&gt; instead.\nWhen a new protagonist is created in \"&lt;a href=\"Shadows%20of%20Amn\"&gt;Shadows of Amn&lt;/a&gt;\", this ability will be granted to them based on their &lt;a href=\"alignment\"&gt;alignment&lt;/a&gt;:"}
{"id": "4692", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4692", "title": "Slow Poison (spell)", "text": "Slow Poison is a 2nd level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt;. It cures both &lt;a href=\"poison\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Intoxicated\"&gt;intoxication&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;a href=\"Dynaheir\"&gt;Dynaheir&lt;/a&gt; may use an &lt;a href=\"innate%20ability\"&gt;innate ability&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Slow%20Poison%20%28ability%29\"&gt;Slow Poison (ability)&lt;/a&gt; once per day. Additionally, &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; may &lt;a href=\"Dreams%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%29\"&gt;gain&lt;/a&gt; uses during the \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\" campaign.\nGameplay.\nContrary to the description, the spell actually removes all &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;poisons&lt;/a&gt;, there are no exceptions (but it will not remove &lt;a href=\"Disease\"&gt;diseases&lt;/a&gt;, which are a different effect). However, the more powerful level 4 spell &lt;a href=\"Neutralize%20Poison\"&gt;Neutralize Poison&lt;/a&gt; additionally heals hit points and also cures diseases and a number of other status effects.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this divine spell, revising its description. See below:\nSlow Poison\nLevel: 2\nSchool: Necromancy\nSphere: Healing\nRange: Touch\nDuration: Instant\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: None\nWhen this spell is cast upon a poisoned individual, it greatly slows the effects of venom, actually neutralizing all but the deadliest poisons."}
{"id": "46348", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=46348", "title": "Slow effect", "text": "Slow is a status effect that doubles the duration of a round only for the creature it is applied to, unless they are explicitly immune to it.\nDouble round duration means that:\nGameplay.\nSince nothing \"cures\" Slow per se, it is advisable to consider the source that applied this magic. More often than not, it is &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;dispellable magic&lt;/a&gt;.\nImmunity to slow can be achieved with various items, but here again it might be worth considering the source trying to apply the magic instead. Maybe it's a spell or a weapon that can be made ineffective."}
