{"id": "47358", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47358", "title": "Smith", "text": "Smith is the name of all three of the blacksmith's that are found in the &lt;a href=\"Thunderhammer%20Smithy\"&gt;Thunderhammer Smithy&lt;/a&gt;. Their dialogue is short and simple. If charmed and spoken too twice, they will give you a set of &lt;a href=\"Chain%20Mail\"&gt;Chain Mail&lt;/a&gt; armor which is unstealable."}
{"id": "11840", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11840", "title": "Smoke Mephit", "text": "A Smoke Mephit is an extra-planar \"outsider\" (i.e., linked to various Elemental, Quasi-Elemental and Outer planes of existence). These creatures are similar to &lt;a href=\"Imp\"&gt;Imps&lt;/a&gt; and are found in a number of areas during the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;\"Baldur's Gate II\"&lt;/a&gt; games. \nGameplay.\nA Smoke Mephit will normally cast an invisibility spell on self when an opponent is detected. The spell is instantly cast. The mephit can attack twice per round in melee for 1d2 damage. It also has the innate &lt;a href=\"Sooty%20Ball\"&gt;Sooty Ball&lt;/a&gt; ability. \nThe mephit will initiate the \"Sooty Ball\" attack right after it turns invisible, as long as there is a detected opponent in range. The ability launches a bullet projectile at a target in range and it deals 1d4 damage. A &lt;a href=\"Blindness\"&gt;Blindness&lt;/a&gt; effect will be applied lasting 10 seconds as well. The crushing attack can be blocked by magic resistance and is a level 2 spell power effect, so that can be stopped by an appropriate spell level protection such as &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;. The Blindness effect has no saving throw, but won't bypass magic resistance. It also has a level 2 spell power.\nThe Smoke Mephit has no magic, or physical damage resistance. \nThe mephit can regenerate 1 hit point every round.\nThe InfoBox summarizes the creature's special abilities and immunities to certain status effects. The creature has an unlimited use of invisibility spells and Sooty ball attacks, with a timed interval of delayed use being the only restriction."}
{"id": "48321", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48321", "title": "Smuggled Shipment", "text": "The Smuggled Shipment is an item needed to satisfy &lt;a href=\"Bodhi\"&gt;Bodhi&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Perform%20Bodhi%27s%20Tasks%20to%20Receive%20Her%20Aid%23Mook\"&gt;first task&lt;/a&gt; if you've decided to side with her and her vampires instead of &lt;a href=\"Aran%20Linvail\"&gt;Aran Linvail&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Thieves\"&gt;Shadow Thieves&lt;/a&gt; in your quest to find &lt;a href=\"Imoen\"&gt;Imoen&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe item is in the possession of the Shadow Thief &lt;a href=\"Mook\"&gt;Mook&lt;/a&gt; who is found at night with several other Shadow Thieves at the Shipyard Docks in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Docks\"&gt;Docks District&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "44911", "revid": "1966519", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=44911", "title": "Smuggler", "text": "\"Smuggler\" is a feller who can be found standing at the southeast end of the &lt;a href=\"Wyrm%27s%20Crossing\"&gt;Wyrm's Crossing&lt;/a&gt; bridge in Chapter 7. He will immediately approach the party upon sight, introduce himself as Tomlin and ask who you happen to be. If you follow the right dialogue option, he will offer to smuggle the party past the &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist\"&gt;Flaming Fist&lt;/a&gt; and into &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;, but in reality, he just walks you across an empty bridge.\nDialogue.\n\"\"Hey there, travelers, y'all seem rather road worn. Perhaps there's a reason for that, eh? Well, I shan't come across as rude: My name's Tomlin, and I'm the owner of a small trading coster that operates out of Beregost. Who do you happen ta be?\""}
{"id": "50207", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50207", "title": "Smuggler's Cave", "text": "Smuggler's Cave is one of two caverns marked on the area map for &lt;a href=\"Amkethran\"&gt;Amkethran&lt;/a&gt;. The remote nature of the village means that Smugglers play a vital role in the supply chain for the village welfare and for its economy. The cavern has access to an underground stream, which the smuggler's utilize as a secret way to move goods in and out of the area, while avoiding Calimshan government and regional taxes and tariffs. It is implied that some of the goods may be contraband or even stolen items. In the recent past, both the Monastery and the Smugglers coexisted without conflict and that helped with the sustainability of the village, all benefitting from the arrangement. However, &lt;a href=\"Balthazar\"&gt;Balthazar&lt;/a&gt; and his current goals have now disrupted the balance in the village, especially with the influx of mercenary forces to fill out a growing Army and plans for war.\nVisiting the Smuggler's Cave.\nThe party may enter the cave at any point in Chapter 8. Upon entry of your party, you will observe the presence of five smugglers, and a few seconds afterwards will appear four monks. No action can be taken as dialogue plays out - you seem to have entered and overhear the lead monk addressing the smuggler leader &lt;a href=\"Carras\"&gt;Carras&lt;/a&gt;. The monk is heard to say, \"\"These mercenaries have filed a complaint that you are selling stolen goods, Carras. This operation is closed, and all merchandise is forfeit to the monastery\".\"\nCarras relies \"\"This is ridiculous! The monastery has never objected to our actions in the past\".\"\nThe monk then says \"\"Tell us where Esamon is Carras, and we will let you go\".\"\nCarras answers \"Esamon isn't here - I haven't seen him in weeks.\"\nThe monk replies \"\"Then I will arrest you instead. For your sake, I hope Esamon shows up before we find it necessary to... interrogate you\".\"\nCarras cries out \"\"No! You can't do this... This is an outrage! When did the monastery become a puppet slave to the whims of a bunch of foreign mercenaries\"?\"\nMonk says \"\"Silence, Carras! Wait... what is this? It seems we have a would-be customer in our midst. The infamous child of Bhaal, if the descriptions of Balthazar are at all accurate.\"\nThe monk continues, addressing your party, \"I could arrest you for being an accessory, Bhaalspawn. However, I am in a generous mood. I suggest you leave now, and don't interfere in our business here\".\"\nThe party now has some dialogue options. To boil it down - you can either leave the monks to their business, or you can let the monks know that you disagree with their actions. You can even do this in a confrontational and insulting way if you prefer. If you don't leave the monks be, then at some juncture of the dialogue the monk leader will shout \"To arms my brothers! we are attacked!\". The monks will become hostile and engage you in melee combat. They will employ &lt;a href=\"Stunning%20Blow\"&gt;Stunning Blow&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Quivering%20Palm\"&gt;Quivering Palm&lt;/a&gt; attacks, so beware. The smugglers do not join the fight. Each defeated monk is worth at least 10,000 XP.\nIf you speak with Carras after the monks are defeated, he says \"\"Thank you for your assistance in this... unpleasant matter. I'm sure that if Esamon were here himself, he would offer his thanks as well\".\"\nYou have a few dialogue options that center on your opinion of Esamon, and if his other name is actually &lt;a href=\"Saemon%20Havarian\"&gt;Saemon Havarian&lt;/a&gt;, and whether you owe him a \"debt of pain\" for past treachery. Carras says to this \"\"Our leader goes by many names, but I assure you I do not know his current whereabouts. Whatever your trouble with Saemon... I had nothing to do with it\".\"\nIf you do not attack or harm the smugglers, you can carry on with interacting with them, and perhaps perform some shopping/selling. Visit &lt;a href=\"Carras\"&gt;Carras&lt;/a&gt; page for further information. Note that the smugglers will only be available for basically one shopping session, and will then leave the cave for good.\nContainers.\nThere are four containers, that look like chests in the rear of the cave. There may be goods or loot in them. You can freely explore these if you wish. Perhaps if your party has one with thieving skills, they should check them first."}
{"id": "42336", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=42336", "title": "Snake", "text": "Snakes are creatures found in the wilderness regions of &lt;a href=\"Siege%20of%20Dragonspear\"&gt;Siege of Dragonspear&lt;/a&gt;, and can be particularly aggressive towards other woodland creatures and occasionally the player. They can be found alone, or in groups. They drop no items."}
{"id": "47623", "revid": "50459896", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47623", "title": "Snow Troll", "text": "Snow Trolls are a species of troll introduced in the . They are only found in the &lt;a href=\"Cloud%20Peaks\"&gt;Cloud Peaks&lt;/a&gt; area which becomes accessible during &lt;a href=\"Rasaad%20yn%20Bashir\"&gt;Rasaad's&lt;/a&gt; side quest &lt;a href=\"The%20Enemies%20of%20My%20Friend\"&gt;The Enemies of My Friend&lt;/a&gt;.\nLike other &lt;a href=\"Troll\"&gt;Troll&lt;/a&gt;s, when brought near to death (a minimum of 1 hit point) they fall unconscious to the ground. They can be killed permanently in that state, but only by &lt;a href=\"Acid%20damage\"&gt;acid&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Fire%20damage\"&gt;fire&lt;/a&gt; damage, and if not done quickly, they recover heath and consciousness."}
