{"id": "5826", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5826", "title": "Spell Deflection", "text": "When Spell Deflection is cast, the wizard is protected by a field of magical energy that deflects incoming spells.\nIt does not protect against most spell protection removers, so it can be dispelled by them instantly, without having to go through the 10 total spell level amount.\nGameplay.\nSpell Deflection protects against spells that are single-target only. It will not offer protection from Area of Effect spells, like for example a &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt; does.\nYou cannot deflect your own spells. But beneficial spells from other allies are deflected.\nIf &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt; is also active, it will be overridden by Spell Deflection. They are not cumulative, negating an incoming spell will drain both at the same time. If both a deflection spell and a turning spell (&lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Minor Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;) are active, then the turning will take priority; while charges of spell turning remain, the spell deflection will not be drained. The spell deflection will only trigger and be drained once the turning effect is exhausted.\nLike most &lt;a href=\"Spell%20protections%20type\"&gt;Spell protections&lt;/a&gt;, spell deflection does not deflect spells that are designed to remove protections, like &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Spellstrike\"&gt;Spellstrike&lt;/a&gt;.\nDivine casters get a similar spell called &lt;a href=\"Shield%20of%20the%20Archons\"&gt;Shield of the Archons&lt;/a&gt;.\nList of spells that can be deflected (innate abilities and enemy-only abilities not included).\nDivine spells:\nLevel 1: Command, Doom, Magic Stone\nLevel 3: Call Lightning (even when you're not the original target), Summon Insects\nLevel 4: Mental Domination, Poison\nLevel 5: Cause Critical Wounds (including from beholder rays), Flame Strike, Slay Living\nLevel 6: Harm, Dolorous Decay, Sol's Searing Orb\nLevel 7: Energy Blades (only the electricity part), Ether Gate, Finger of Death, Implosion\nArcane Spells:\nLevel 1: Blindness, Charm Person, Chill Touch (not the fist damage), Chromatic Orb, Larloch's Minor Drain, Magic Missile, Shocking Grasp (not the fist damage), Spook\nLevel 2: Agannazar's Scorcher (even when you're not the original target), Deafness, Ghoul Touch (not the fist damage), Melf's Acid Arrow, Power Word: Sleep, Ray of Enfeeblement\nLevel 3: Dire Charm, Flame Arrow, Lightning Bolt (only if you're the original target), Melf's Minute Meteors (only the fire damage), Vampiric Touch\nLevel 4: Contagion, Fireshield: Blue and Red, Polymorph Other\nLevel 5: Domination, Feeblemind\nLevel 6: Chain Lightning (only if you're the original target), Disintegrate, Flesh to Stone, Power Word: Silence\nLevel 7: Finger of Death, Power Word: Stun\nLevel 8: Bigby's Clenched Fist, Maze, Power Word: Blind\nLevel 9: Bigby's Crushing Hand, Black Blade of Disaster (protects against the level drain and disintegration), Energy Blades (only the electricity part), Energy Drain, Imprisonment, Power Word: Kill\nIt will also deflect enemy abilities that count as spells of these &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;power levels&lt;/a&gt;, for example &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;Beholder&lt;/a&gt; rays.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; (SCS) changes Spell Deflection behavior and now protects against the 5th Level Breach spell and the Wand of Spell Striking.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod uses a spell of the same name, but it replaces &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Minor Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;, which is removed from the game."}
{"id": "5884", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5884", "title": "Spell Immunity", "text": "Spell Immunity grants protection from spells and abilities of one spell school of the wizard's choosing.\nGameplay.\nThe caster applies this spell to self only.\nWhen the spell casting is finished a brief lighting renders on the caster, as well as a sound effect will audible.\nAt this time a text is displayed, reading \"Spell Immunity &lt;CASTER NAME&gt;\" - a sub menu is seen at the bottom of the main screen's text box with eight icons representing each spell school.\nUsing the selection cursor, choose one of the icons - click on it to initiate the next phase of the spell, a text will display reading &lt;CASTER NAME&gt; Casts Immunity: &lt;SPELL SCHOOL&gt;: &lt;SPELL RECIPENT'S NAME&gt;.\nThe spell's 3D graphic effect will be rendered on the sprite for the duration of the spell, or until the spell is removed (a swirling white energy field).\nA player character will show an icon on their portrait titled as Immunity: &lt;Spell School&gt;, for example - Immunity: Abjuration.\nSpell Immunity protects the caster from all spells, abilities, item abilities and weapon on-hit effects as long as they fit all three conditions:\nSpell immunity protects against single-target effects and those applied in an Area of Effect.\nThis &lt;a href=\"Spell%20protections%20type\"&gt;Spell protection&lt;/a&gt; can block both single target and &lt;a href=\"Game%20Terminology%23A\"&gt;AoE&lt;/a&gt; attacks of any level. When Spell Immunity successfully blocks something, the line \"Spell Ineffective\" appears in the combat logs.\nSpell Immunity itself can be removed by an appropriate &lt;a href=\"Magic%20attack%20type\"&gt;Magic attack type&lt;/a&gt; spell - such as &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Thrust\"&gt;Spell Thrust&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Secret%20Word\"&gt;Secret Word&lt;/a&gt;, and more.\nSpell Immunity can be defended from being removed by including a &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Shield\"&gt;Spell Shield&lt;/a&gt; to cancel a Magic attack type spell protection remover from getting to the Spell Immunity.\nThis is just part of the \"mage chess\" dynamic that the Baldur's Gate magic system has implemented in the game.\nNotes.\nAll are able to destroy Spell Immunity. Nothing else can. This spell can be very useful:\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced D&amp;D 2nd Edition Wizard spell &lt;a href=\"https%3A//adnd2e.fandom.com/wiki/Spell_Immunity_%28Wizard_Spell%29\"&gt;\"Spell Immunity\"&lt;/a&gt; is substantially different than the Bioware version implemented in the game - the tabletop rules restrict its use to a specific spell that the wizard has had exposure to before and doesn't protect against a broad sphere of spells or an entire school of magic. The BG video game's spell version is quite the jump in power from the pen and paper game. \nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod, as of the Nov 2023 release, makes a change so that Breach now bypasses spell immunity by being effectively level 10. \n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has replaced the \"Spell Immunity\" spell with \"Dispelling Screen\". See below for description:\nDispelling Screen\nLevel: 5\nSchool: Abjuration\nRange: Personal\nDuration: 5 turns\nCasting Time: 5\nArea of Effect: Caster and nearby allies\nSaving Throw: None\nBy casting this spell, caster creates a transparent, permeable barrier that shields the caster and allies from Dispel Magic and Breach spells. The barrier dissipates after one instance of Dispel Magic or Breach. Spells higher in power that remove specific protections like Pierce Shield and Spellstrike remove Dispelling Screen from target without getting absorbed by it."}
{"id": "22152", "revid": "50866439", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=22152", "title": "Spell Progression (wizard)", "text": "The wizard spell progression table is based on the \"MXSPLWIZ.2da\" game file. It determines the level and number of &lt;a href=\"spells\"&gt;spells&lt;/a&gt; a wizard is able to memorize at which &lt;a href=\"Experience%20Tables\"&gt;experience level&lt;/a&gt; of their wizard &lt;a href=\"Classes\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Mage\"&gt;Generalist mages&lt;/a&gt; refer to this, as well as all characters with a \"mage\" component in their &lt;a href=\"Classes%23Multi-class\"&gt;multi-class&lt;/a&gt; combination. &lt;a href=\"Specialist%20Mage\"&gt;Specialist&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Wild%20Mage\"&gt;wild mages&lt;/a&gt; also use this table, though they add one slot to all numbers greater than zero.\nLevel caps.\nIn the various of the \"Baldur's Gate\" series single- and multi-class mages can reach different experience levels, hence having access to varying levels of spells. In general at every second experience level the next spell level gets unlocked \u2013 spell level 1 at XP level 1, spell level 2 at XP level 3, spell level 3 at XP level 5, and so on \u2013, with one break: access to spell level 6 is only gained at XP level 12 instead of 11. To get spells of the highest level, 9, a character has to reach experience level 18 for their wizard class.\nWhich layout to take?\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\" the highest obtainable wizard levels are 7 for single-class wizards, 6 for dual multi-classes and 5 for the &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Mage%20/%20Thief\"&gt;Fighter / Mage / Thief&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Mage%20/%20Cleric\"&gt;Fighter / Mage / Cleric&lt;/a&gt;. In ' and the ' they are 9, 7 and 6 respectively. In ' they are 11, 10 and 9. In ' they are 17, 13 and 12. In ' and the ' they are 31, 20 and 17. In \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Black%20Pits\"&gt;The Black Pits&lt;/a&gt;\" it is level 10 for single-class wizards and &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Mage\"&gt;Fighter / Mage&lt;/a&gt;s, level 9 for Fighter / Mage / Cleric and Fighter / Mage / Thief and level 8 for &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20/%20Mage\"&gt;Cleric / Mage&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Mage%20/%20Thief\"&gt;Mage / Thief&lt;/a&gt;.\nSpell progression tables by class.\nTable for basic mages.\nThe following table lists the number of memorizable spells of each spell level for a character with the according experience level in their wizard class. A pure &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; can reach a maximum level of 33 in , which is where this table ends. \n&lt;onlyinclude&gt;\n&lt;/onlyinclude&gt;\n&lt;onlyinclude&gt;\nTable for &lt;a href=\"Specialist%20Mage\"&gt;specialist&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Wild%20Mage\"&gt;wild mage&lt;/a&gt;s.\n&lt;/onlyinclude&gt;\nTable for sorcerers.\nFor the spell progression table for sorcerers, see table #2 &lt;a href=\"https%3A//baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki/Sorcerer%23Spell_progression\"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "4094", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4094", "title": "Spell Progression Tables", "text": "The spell progression tables tell how &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"sorcerer\"&gt;sorcerer&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"druid\"&gt;druid&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"bard\"&gt;bard&lt;/a&gt;,\u00a0&lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"ranger\"&gt;ranger&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"shaman\"&gt;shaman&lt;/a&gt; class gain more spellslot(s) and of which spell level(s), and learn new spells. Spellslots define how often spells of that spell level can be cast per day. Sorcerers and Shamans also have a \"spells known\" mechanic, where they learn new spells when leveling up and are limited to those.\nBesides the level-based progression listed here, only Clerics and Druids additionally can gain more spell slots from their Wisdom &lt;a href=\"Ability%20Scores\"&gt;ability score&lt;/a&gt; (see the &lt;a href=\"Wisdom\"&gt;Wisdom&lt;/a&gt; article for the table). Mages, Sorcerers and Bards do not gain slots from their &lt;a href=\"Intelligence\"&gt;Intelligence&lt;/a&gt; or other scores, and neither do Paladins, Rangers and Shamans. Mages and Sorcerers can however gain additional slots as &lt;a href=\"high-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;high-level class ability&lt;/a&gt;, and most classes can use certain items (listed at the end of this article) to gain additional spell slots.\nMage.\nCompared to a generalist &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Wild%20Mage\"&gt;Wild Mage&lt;/a&gt;s gain one extra spellslot for each spell level. So do\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Specialist%20Mage\"&gt;Specialist Mage&lt;/a&gt;s,\u00a0but at the cost of not being able to cast spells from certain schools.\nAll mages can get one additional slot for spell levels 6, 7 and 8 each by taking the respective &lt;a href=\"high-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;high-level class ability&lt;/a&gt;.\nMages don't learn new spells at levelup, instead they copy them from scrolls. The amount of spells they can know is based on their &lt;a href=\"Intelligence\"&gt;Intelligence&lt;/a&gt;.\nSorcerer.\n&lt;a href=\"Sorcerer%23Dragon%20Disciple%20%28EE%20only%29\"&gt;Dragon Disciple&lt;/a&gt;s have one less spell ready to cast per day at each spell level to trade for other\u00a0benefits. They have the same amount of spells known as normal &lt;a href=\"Sorcerer\"&gt;Sorcerers&lt;/a&gt;.\nSorcerers and Dragon Disciples must select new spells when leveling up and can not learn any other spells, except for which they can add as &lt;a href=\"high-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;high-level class ability&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;a href=\"Sorcerer\"&gt;Sorcerer&lt;/a&gt;s can reach level 9 in ', level 11 in ', level 17 in ', level 31 in ' and the \"\", and level 10 in \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Black%20Pits\"&gt;The Black Pits&lt;/a&gt;\".\nSorcerers and dragon disciples can get one additional daily casting for spell levels 6, 7 and 8 each by taking the respective &lt;a href=\"high-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;high-level class ability&lt;/a&gt;.\n\"* Plus HLA spells, so in total 9 level 9 spells can be known.\"\nCleric.\n&lt;a href=\"Cleric\"&gt;Cleric&lt;/a&gt;s gain additional spell slots by their\u00a0&lt;a href=\"wisdom\"&gt;wisdom&lt;/a&gt; score. Clerics automatically know all spells of the spell levels they have access to.\nDruid.\n&lt;a href=\"Druid\"&gt;Druid&lt;/a&gt;s gain additional spell slots by their\u00a0&lt;a href=\"wisdom\"&gt;wisdom&lt;/a&gt; score. They automatically know all spells of the spell levels they have access to.\nBard.\n&lt;a href=\"Bard\"&gt;Bard&lt;/a&gt;s use &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; spells. Like mages, they also copy their spells from scrolls.\nPaladin.\n&lt;a href=\"Paladin\"&gt;Paladin&lt;/a&gt;s use\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Cleric\"&gt;priest&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0spells.\nRanger.\n&lt;a href=\"Ranger\"&gt;Ranger&lt;/a&gt;s use\u00a0&lt;a href=\"druid\"&gt;druid&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0spells.\nShaman.\n&lt;a href=\"Shaman\"&gt;Shaman&lt;/a&gt;s use &lt;a href=\"druid\"&gt;druid&lt;/a&gt; spells, as well as their own unique shaman spells which they automatically get. Like Sorcerers, they have to select spells when leveling up and are limited to those.\n\"* Plus up to eight are added on top to the known spells of spell level 7.\"\nSpell access by XP.\nHow many experience points are required for each class to unlock new spell levels:\nItems that grant additional spell slots.\nArcane:\n\"Note: Bards only profit from additional spell slots up to spell level 6, they won't be able to cast higher-level spells even with items that give high-level slots. Bards can however take &lt;a href=\"Use%20Any%20Item\"&gt;Use Any Item&lt;/a&gt; to wear those normally mage-restricted items that grant bonus slots for spell levels 1-6 and profit from those.\" \n\"Note: &lt;a href=\"Mage%20/%20Thief\"&gt;Mage / Thief&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Mage%20/%20Thief\"&gt;Fighter / Mage / Thief&lt;/a&gt; can also select &lt;a href=\"Use%20Any%20Item\"&gt;Use Any Item&lt;/a&gt; to use the bard-only Wondrous Gloves for extra spell slots.\" \nDivine:\n\"Note: &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20/%20Thief\"&gt;Cleric / Thieves&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a href=\"Use%20Any%20Item\"&gt;Use Any Item&lt;/a&gt; can benefit from the extra slots of Druid-only items.\""}
{"id": "49506", "revid": "35642161", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49506", "title": "Spell Revisions", "text": "The Spell Revisions mod (\"SR\") aims to fix, tweak, and enhance arcane and divine spells in Baldur's Gate II, Tutu, and Baldur's Gate Trilogy. This originally started as a project to make the spell system more balanced by improving weaker spells and nerfing overpowered ones - but has evolved to also include changes to spells designed to make them more fun and interesting and fixes for spell-related bugs found in the original game.\nMain Component.\nSpell Revisions places a high priority on making all of the existing spells viable choices, while keeping an eye on balance issues. Now, Magic Missile won't be the only first-level arcane spell you'll want to memorize! To help achieve this goal, portions of the old spell system that were consistently underpowered, like healing spells and summons, have been vastly improved so that they are competitive options. In addition, SR takes the stance that low-level spells should not become completely ineffective once characters reach higher levels, so it adds scaling features to many spells.\nAmong other things, the mod makes druid and cleric spell selections more distinct, with druids focusing on animal and elemental spheres for a repertoire of spells oriented toward the offensive. Arcane spell schools have also been flushed out, with the belief that each spell level should contain at least one spell from each school. To help fulfill these goals, SR adds a small number of spells to the game and modifies the schools and restrictions of some existing spells where appropriate.\nSR also improves the descriptions of many spells to be more accurate, more consistent, and, occasionally, less boring.\nAdditional Content.\nSpell Revisions includes several optional components that do not require the main component.\nDeva and Planetar Avatars.\nThis component updates the avatars of the celestials summoned by HLAs to take advantage of 1PP Attachable Wings and adjusts the weapons they use.\nMirror Image Fix.\nThis component fixes mirror images so they no longer protect from AoE spells such as Fireball.\nDispel Magic Fix.\nThis component fixes the chance to dispel magic to match the spell's description (so there is at least a marginal chance of dispelling effects of a higher-level mage) and corrects conceptual problems caused by the automatic dispelling of all magically created items.\nSupplements.\nUpdate Spellbooks of Joinable NPCs.\nThis component requires that the main component be installed.\u00a0 It patches all joinable NPC spellcasters in the game, updating their spellbooks by removing spells that should no longer be available to them and adding new ones they should have. This component should be installed after any mod NPCs are installed.\nFor more information see the Links below:"}
